snippet.textDisplay: Sohni Mahiwal is one of Punjab’s most famous folk love tales. Sohni, the beautiful daughter of a potter from the Gujjar clan, captured the heart of a trader named Izzat (later called Mahiwal) who had come from Iran or Kashmir to buy pots. They fell deeply in love, and Mahiwal gave up his wealth and settled on the banks of the Chenab River, living a simple life. When Sohni’s parents discovered the love affair, they forcibly married her within their own community, but her heart remained with Mahiwal. Every night, she would secretly cross the Chenab on a baked clay pot to meet him. One day, her sister-in-law replaced the baked pot with an unbaked one that could not withstand water. That night, as Sohni tried to cross, the pot began to dissolve in the middle of the river. Realizing the betrayal, she cried: “Today I must meet my beloved, otherwise he will only receive my dead body.” She began to drown, and Mahiwal, waiting on the other side, jumped into the river to save her, but both perished in the waters. Their tragic love remains a symbol of sacrifice, loyalty, and eternal passion, remembered alongside other legendary romances like Heer Ranjha and Sassi Punnu.
